metadata.name: Modulation #115
metadata.description:
Isometric cityscapes, patterns and geometries generated by trigonometric functions and rendered as SVG.

The SVG can be saved by pressing "s" on the full-screen view.
A PNG version can be exported by pressing "e" on the full-screen view.

By default the dimensions of the export are 6000√ó7500.
These dimensions can be changed by adding, for example, ?w=12000 to the full-screen page URL, where w is the desired width. Then press "e" to export at this size.

metadata.name: Tema #30
metadata.description:
Tema is the second in a set of collections based on a month-long study of Edward Zajec, one of the early pioneers of generative art in the 1970s.

After gaining some traction with his original collection RAM, Zajec and his collaborating programmer Matjaz Hmeljak undertook a more complex algorithm titled "The Cube: Theme and Variation" (or TVC). The program laid out 8 unique elements in a grid, creating a three-dimensional viewing of objects in space. They published a paper about the underlying algorithm, found at: http://www.edwardzajec.com/tvc4/pil1/index.html

TVC was first printed in 1971, shortly after Zajec returned to Italy following his artistic studies in the US. It was programmed on an IBM 9044 & printed with a CalComp 563 plotter.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save a high-resolution version of the image

Made in p5js
Created January 2023
By @christine_hall

metadata.name: Blurevich #118
metadata.description:
"Blurevich"

The painting is characterized by its non-representational style, where the rectangles are not meant to depict recognizable objects or figures. 
Instead, the blurred rectangles serve as visual elements that create a sense of movement and dynamism in the painting. 
The use of blurriness in the rectangles gives the painting a hazy and ethereal quality. 
The colors used in the painting would  be bold and striking, creating a striking contrast between the sharp edges of the rectangles and the soft, blurred edges. 
The overall effect of the painting is one of abstraction and experimentation, express our emotions.

metadata.name: Sand #55
metadata.description:
This project is a cellular automata that simulates falling sand. The falling is deterministic: each sand particle will fall to the same place each time the program is run. Some iterations eventually stop, some continue indefinitely.

The fun is that the project is implemented on a fragment shader. There is no array of grains of sand. Each pixel decides whether a grain of sand from a neighboring pixel will end up in it or not. This logic required a lot of banging my head against the wall, because the slightest mistake caused sand to disappear into nowhere or appear out of nothing and clutter up the entire space.

space ‚Äî pause
s ‚Äî save picture
drag over ‚Äî add more sand

metadata.name: Kinetic Bug #140
metadata.description:
Best viewed on a decent GPU,  because physics simulations are performance intensive. Otherwise you might encounter a bug...

In a world of digital data, a new life is born. We are not alone...
Explore how kinetic bugs make their way through the world. What will their destiny be?
It's curious that we can sympathize to a predefined creature living it's predestined life in the digital world. Coding in the computer abyss reveals interesting worlds.

Keyboard
[ space ] - jump
[ click ] - increase velocity briefly
[ r ] - restart simulation
[ s ] - save image
[ f ] - full screen

Mobile
[ two finger tap ] - jump
[ tap ] - increase velocity briefly

Created with Three.js + rapier.js
Copyright (c) July 2022 Shaderism

metadata.name: CHIP #150
metadata.description:
A CHIP is being constructed by using two brushes that are painting on the board through deterministic noise, and then turned squared and pixelated and blended into each other, with colours selected from 21 different colour schemes. How many iterations, and the speed and size of the added parts determines the final composition. 

You can stop the iterations by pressing S, and download the current composition by hitting D, and restart/reload the iterations by pressing R.

Notes
The thumbnail generation takes a while and the render/iterations in non-GPU browser can be quite slow. Chrome/Firefox recommended.

metadata.name: Sketches:Pairs of Tails:Majestic Creatures #29
metadata.description:
Addendum to Annuls of WorSAGE (the Worshipful Society of Adventurers and Generative Explorers) XXVII.Vol.2048

There is a significantly common phenomena in which Pairs of "Tails of Majestic Creatures" are found together. Various sketches of these "Pairs" have been collated and are available, free of charge, the collectors of the initial Tails of Majestic Creatures collection based upon a recently taken collection registry snapshot. 

These sketches are available on a one per collector basis and for a limited time only after which they will no longer be accessible.

The sketches come in 2 forms - an ink and color style, and a pencil style - for which different colored paper has been used.

The digitally minded can press s to get a 5000x3000 download of a sketch.
